text: Fifth Avenue, east side, north from and including 26th Street, showing the N.W. corner of Madison Square and the Hotel Brunswick on the N.E. corner of 26th Street. According to King's Handbook of New York (1892), parades of the Coaching Club always started in front of the Brunswick, and he mentions it as much favored by English tourists. This photograph was taken by one of such Englishman, and was annotated in his own writing "Where I stayed with Lucas C. E. en route from Venezuela to England". About 1906 this building will be replaced by the 12-story Brunswick Building, as Madison Square changes into a strictly business district. 1888.

Fifth Avenue, west side, from west 26th (left) to 27th Streets, showing prominently the Hotel Brunswick.  This is the S.W. corner of 27th Street (right).  Grover Cleveland, on his election to the Presidency, made it his headquarters in New York.

About 1890.

Gift of Urbrock Collection

Fifth Avenue, west side, at W. 26th Street, showing Delmonico's at the left. This building extends on the south side of 26th Street to Broadway. Soon after this photograph was made, the establishment moved to the N.E. corner of Fifth Avenue and E. 44th Street, where it remained until its demise at the hands of prohibition.

About 1893

text:
26th Street east from Fifth Avenue, taken from roof of the Cafe Martin. This picture gives a good view of Madison Square Garden (1889-1925), and the lovely Diana of St. Gaudens, poised atop its tower. The Garden was acquired by the New York Life Insurance Company in 1915 at a foreclosure sale, and in 1920 was saved from demolition by Tex Rickard, who signed a ten year lease on it. In 1924 the New York Life bought back this lease and in 1925 tore down the Garden, to build their present edifice on its site. Diana, however, is still to be seen in Fairmont Park, Philadelphia. In the centre, with the Uneeda Biscuit sign on its roof, is the Hotel Brunswick, and at the extreme left is the Hotel Victoria, made famous by the patronage of President Cleveland. To the right of the Garden is the former Jerome residence, later the University Club and now (1935) the Manhattan Club. About 1898.

Browning Studios.

Fifth Avenue at S.W. corner of 26th Street, showing Café Martin, a famous restaurant, which at the time of this picture has only recently taken this building over from Delmonico's.  It will be demolished in 1912 to make room for a modern office building.

The building which has just been demolished will be replaced by the 12-story Cross Chambers building (Mark Cross & Co.).  See the oversize pictures of this block in 1902 and 1912.

In the right background is shown the St. James Building at Broadway and 26th Street, on the site of the old St. James Hotel.  [Sic- it's the Townsend Building in right background. St. James Bldg is NW cr 25th & B'way.]

April 1902.
